I have a detached ACL in my left knee, a bit of osteoarthritis in both knees,  two detach rotator cuff muscles in my left shoulder, and a detached bicep muscle in my left bicep. value: I'd like to feel happy again. I know that's a big ask, but if I were to 'genie in a bottle' be granted a wish, it would be to have my happiness back. I have gone to more doctors than I can count to help with my multiple ailments. I was diagnosed with lupus March 11 of 2021 after having severe nausea, severe fatigue, butterfly rashes on face and back, aches and pains, inability to use restroom and extreme headaches. My aunt had passed away from Lupus about 5 years prior after battling for around 40 years. Her lupus specifically attacked her DNA, heart and lungs. I've tried to get help: an endocrinologist, rheumatologist, neurologist, gastroentolosist... you name it. every doctor has accessed my issues and tried to 'solve the problem' from their specific point of view. the gastro gave me all of the prescription laxatives, nothing worked. I once went 20 days without using the restroom and was at the point of extreme agony and inability to eat. he found nothing wrong after sticking microscopes and cameras into my gut and system. my endocrinologist ran tests on me and found that I am not producing almost any amount of Seratonin, dopamine, glycine, n-methylihistamine, DOPAC, HVA, Norephinephrine, Normetanephrine, epinephrine, VMA, Kynurenic Acid, Free Cortisone(morning), and free cortisone(2nd morning).Other factors like PEA,Tyrosine, Glutamine, GABA, 5-HIAA, and Tryptophan are bordering the 'red zone'. She had no answers for me besides to take Welbutrin and a neuro motility drug called Linzess(290mg). So as you can see, happiness is a problem for me and I couldn't be more grateful for my life and the people in it. It just feels like somethings missing. I'm willing to try anything.

key: What is the biggest goal or improvement you'd like to focus on while working with Lifeforce?
What is your biggest complaint or concern you would like to address while working with Lifeforce?
value:
I've been breastfeeding since my daughter was born in August 2021 (she is almost 2). We have started weaning, but I am still breastfeeding 3x/day. My menstrual cycle has not returned. As I understand it, I'm just one of those women whose cycle is halted while breastfeeding. Once my daughter is completely weaned, we would like to try to conceive again. Out of curiosity, I started taking my basal body temperature (BBT) using a device called TempDrop (I wear it throughout the night and it syncs with an app to record my BBT). My BBTs have consistently been in the 95-96 degree range. This seemed low to me. When I looked into it, hypothyroidism kept coming up in my research. Other things I have experienced lately include bouts of depressed mood, brain fog, and fatigue. Up until now, I just attributed these symptoms to general sleep deprivation (my almost 2-year-old has never been a great sleeper, but she is night weaned and now we're both sleeping through the night). 

All that being said, I wonder if I do have an underlying thyroid issue. Interestingly, in August 2018, I was in a car accident and had a CT scan of my neck performed. 
These findings are copy and pasted from the CT scan note: 
"Study Result
Impression
1. No acute C-spine fracture or traumatic subluxation
identified.

2. Atrophic appearing thyroid gland, raising the possibility
of sequelae from prior thyroiditis. Correlated with thyroid
function.

3. A 3 to 4 mm soft tissue nodule in the right paratracheal
region that could represent incidental lymph node, normal
parathyroid gland, or possibly a small parathyroid adenoma.

Narrative
EXAMINATION: CT cervical spine without contrast.

CLINICAL INFORMATION: Trauma.

COMPARISON: None.

TECHNIQUE: Contiguous axially or helically acquired images
cervical spine followed by multiplanar reformatted images.

This CT exam was performed using one or more of the
following dose-reduction techniques: Automated exposure
control, adjustment of the mA and/or kV according to patient
size, and/or use of iterative reconstruction technique.

FINDINGS:
Alignment: There is no significant vertebral subluxation.

Atlanto-axial and atlanto-occipital joints: Atlanto-axial
and atlanto-occipital intervals are not widened.

Discs: Preserved. Mild bulging disc margins.

Facet joints: There is no traumatic facet joint widening.
Mild facet arthropathy at right C5-C6.

Vertebral bodies: The vertebral bodies are maintained in
height and attenuation.

Spinal canal and foraminal narrowing: Although CT does not
optimally evaluate the soft tissue contents of the spinal
canal and foramina, no critical stenosis is suggested.

Fractures: No acute cervical spine fracture is present.

Paraspinal soft tissues: The thyroid gland is unusually
small for age, suggesting atrophy. This may represent
sequelae of prior thyroiditis. Minor apical scarring noted.
A 3 to 4 mm soft tissue nodule is noted in the right
paratracheal region posterior to the thyroid gland. This
could represent an incidental lymph node, normal parathyroid
gland, or possibly a parathyroid adenoma. Scattered upper
limits of normal by size criteria cervical lymph nodes are
noted, statistically likely reactive."

Results from follow-up testing at that time were "normal" according to doctors. 

Ultimately, I would like to better understand if I have any underlying thyroid issues, as I know that can impact my ability to get pregnant again.

key: What is your biggest complaint or concern you would like to address while working with Lifeforce?
value:
I have trouble exercising because of  a posterior tendon rupture (right leg), torn ACL (right leg, horizontal tears in both medial meniscus(es) (both knees).  I wear a right ankle foot brace and various knee supports.  It is tough to go for a walk because after about 100' my brace starts to wear on my heel and raise blisters and I'm instructed to wear this brace whenever I'm walking.  I know, why don't I get these things fixed with easily available out patient surgery?  

Because my cardiologist insists that I must have an aortic valve replacement first.  This from my a recent echogram.  She will not approve any other procedures until I do the TAVR.  I've had a murmur for years that suggested this possibility but I'd really like to intuitively feel better about this procedure (I definitely do not) and I think I should perhaps be experiencing some symptoms for a stenotic aortic valve before I have a procedure  that is likely to keep me in a nursing home for some time being rehabbed or at least rehabilitating their financial statement.  Perhaps I should buy an exercise bike and give up the dream of long walks again.

A relative who is a lawyer has had several cases she pursued where this procedure had failed for her clients.  And, she loves regaling me with these stories.  

My cardiologist tells me that 90% of the TAVRs with which she's associated are successful and 50% of those who need a TAVR and don't get one die in two years.  In researching this, the NIH has reported that 25% of those receiving TAVRs die in the first two years after the procedure.

An important  fact here is I just turned 83.  1940 was a good year.  Actuary tables aren't that generous to me about life expectancy at this stage anyway.  So here is my Goal.
I would like to live as healthily as possible as to life style, I don't drink, smoke or use recreational (?) drugs, never have.   I have been working for the last six months to improve my health using diet, exercise, supplements, and meditation and mindfulness and enjoy what's left of my nice ol' body for as long as I can with no serious surgery that has a good chance of rendering me incapacitated physically or mentally.

And that's my concern.
